SIMPLE: sleeper
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sleeper
<hw>Sleep"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who
sleeps; a slumberer; hence, a drone, or lazy person.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which lies dormant, as a law.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sleeping car.</def> <mark>[Colloq.
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An animal that hibernates, as the
bear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A large fresh-water
gobioid fish (<spn>Eleotris dormatrix</spn>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A
nurse shark. See under <er>Nurse</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sleeper</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sleeper
<hw>Sleep"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Norw. <ets>sleip</ets> a
sleeper (a timber), as adj., slippery, smooth. See
<er>Slape</er>.]</ety> <def>Something lying in a reclining posture or
position.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>One of the pieces of timber, stone, or iron, on or
near the level of the ground, for the support of some superstructure, to
steady framework, to keep in place the rails of a railway, etc.; a
stringpiece.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of the joists, or roughly shaped timbers, laid
directly upon the ground, to receive the flooring of the ground
story.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>One of the knees which connect
the transoms to the after timbers on the ship's quarter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The lowest, or bottom, tier of
casks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sleepful</ent>⟦br⟧
